{
  "Hurricanes require ocean surface temperatures of at least:": "",
  "10 degrees Celsius": "",
  "20 degrees Celsius": "",
  "26.5 degrees Celsius": "",
  "35 degrees Celsius": "",
  "Hurricanes need ocean surface temperatures of at least 26.5 degrees Celsius to provide sufficient energy through evaporation and the release of latent heat when water vapor condenses in the storm's thunderstorms.": "",
  "The calm center of a hurricane is called the:": "",
  "Front": "",
  "Eye": "",
  "Funnel": "",
  "Wall cloud": "",
  "The eye is the calm, clear center of a hurricane where air sinks and conditions are relatively peaceful, surrounded by the eyewall which contains the most intense winds and heaviest rainfall in the entire storm.": "",
  "Storm surge is the number one cause of hurricane deaths because it:": "",
  "Generates lightning strikes in coastal areas": "",
  "Produces a dome of ocean water pushed ashore by hurricane winds, causing massive coastal flooding": "",
  "Creates sinkholes along the shoreline": "",
  "Creates extremely cold temperatures along the coast": "",
  "Storm surge is a rise of water generated by a hurricane's winds pushing ocean water toward shore, and it can raise water levels by several meters, flooding coastal areas far inland and causing more fatalities than any other hurricane hazard.": "",
  "Tornadoes most commonly form in association with:": "",
  "Supercell thunderstorms": "",
  "Hurricanes only": "",
  "Clear weather conditions": "",
  "High pressure systems": "",
  "Most significant tornadoes form from supercell thunderstorms, which contain a persistent rotating updraft called a mesocyclone that can tighten and extend to the ground as a tornado.": "",
  "Category 5 hurricanes on the Saffir-Simpson scale have sustained winds of:": "",
  "252+ km/h": "",
  "119 km/h": "",
  "500 km/h": "",
  "180 km/h": "",
  "Category 5 is the highest rating on the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale, with sustained winds of 252 km/h (157 mph) or greater, capable of catastrophic destruction including complete roof failure and structural collapse of buildings.": "",
  "Tornado Alley in the United States includes parts of:": "",
  "Alaska, particularly regarding": "",
  "The Great Plains from Texas to Nebraska": "",
  "The Pacific Coast when": "",
  "New England, particularly": "",
  "Tornado Alley spans the Great Plains from Texas to Nebraska, where warm, moist maritime tropical air from the Gulf of Mexico frequently collides with cold, dry continental polar air from Canada, creating the atmospheric instability needed for supercell thunderstorms and tornadoes.": "",
  "A tornado watch means:": "",
  "A tornado has been sighted and you should take shelter immediately": "",
  "The tornado danger has passed and it is safe to go outside": "",
  "Atmospheric conditions are favorable for tornado development and you should be prepared": "",
  "Mild thunderstorms are expected with no tornado risk": "",
  "A tornado watch means conditions are favorable for tornado development in the designated area, so people should stay alert, monitor weather reports, and be prepared to take shelter if a warning is issued.": "",
  "Doppler radar detects tornadoes by measuring:": "",
  "Wind velocity and direction, identifying rotation within storms": "",
  "Atmospheric pressure changes": "",
  "Cloud height and temperature": "",
  "Only the amount of rainfall": "",
  "Doppler radar measures both the location and velocity of precipitation particles, allowing meteorologists to detect rotation within thunderstorms by identifying areas where winds are moving toward and away from the radar in close proximity.": "",
  "Hurricanes weaken rapidly when they:": "",
  "Encounter another hurricane": "",
  "Move toward the equator": "",
  "Move over land or cold water, cutting off their warm water energy source": "",
  "Move over warmer ocean water": "",
  "Hurricanes derive their energy from warm ocean water, so when they move over land (which provides no moisture) or over cold water (which provides insufficient energy), they lose their fuel source and weaken rapidly.": "",
  "An EF5 tornado has estimated winds of:": "",
  "150 km/h": "",
  "200 km/h": "",
  "Over 322 km/h": "",
  "65 km/h": "",
  "EF5 tornadoes, the most powerful on the Enhanced Fujita scale, have estimated winds exceeding 322 km/h (200 mph) and can cause incredible destruction, leveling well-built homes and throwing vehicles hundreds of meters.": "",
  "What is a tornado warning?": "",
  "An urgent alert that a tornado has been sighted or detected on radar and people should take shelter immediately": "",
  "A notification that a tornado threat has passed": "",
  "An advisory that conditions may become favorable for tornadoes in the coming hours": "",
  "A long-range forecast that tornado season is approaching": "",
  "A tornado warning is more urgent than a watch and means a tornado has been sighted by a trained spotter or indicated by Doppler radar, requiring people in the warning area to take immediate shelter in an interior room on the lowest floor.": "",
  "What is a blizzard?": "",
  "A severe winter storm with sustained winds of at least 56 km/h, heavy or blowing snow, and visibility below 400 meters for at least 3 hours": "",
  "Any weather event with temperatures below negative 20 degrees Celsius": "",
  "Any snowstorm that produces more than 10 cm of snow": "",
  "A cold-weather tornado that forms over snow-covered ground": "",
  "A blizzard is defined by specific criteria: sustained winds or frequent gusts of at least 56 km/h (35 mph), considerable falling or blowing snow, and visibility reduced to less than 400 meters (one-quarter mile) for at least three hours.": "",
  "What is a derecho?": "",
  "A type of hurricane that forms over land": "",
  "A winter storm that produces both snow and freezing rain": "",
  "A widespread, long-lived windstorm associated with a fast-moving band of severe thunderstorms producing straight-line winds": "",
  "A small, localized tornado that lasts only a few seconds": "",
  "A derecho is a widespread, long-lived windstorm produced by a fast-moving band of severe thunderstorms (called a squall line or bow echo), with damaging straight-line winds of at least 93 km/h that can cause destruction over a path hundreds of kilometers long.": "",
  "What is a mesocyclone?": "",
  "The calm eye of a hurricane": "",
  "A rotating updraft within a supercell thunderstorm that can lead to tornado formation": "",
  "A small low pressure system that forms over the ocean": "",
  "The circular wind pattern in a blizzard": "",
  "A mesocyclone is a rotating updraft within a supercell thunderstorm, typically 2 to 10 km in diameter, that develops when wind shear causes the updraft to spin, and it is the precursor to tornado formation when the rotation tightens and descends.": "",
  "What is the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale?": "",
  "A scale that rates storm surge height from hurricanes": "",
  "A system that predicts how many hurricanes will form each season": "",
  "A scale that measures the size of hurricanes by their diameter": "",
  "A 1-to-5 rating system that categorizes hurricanes based on their sustained wind speed and estimated potential damage": "",
  "The Saffir-Simpson scale rates hurricanes from Category 1 (119-153 km/h winds) to Category 5 (252+ km/h winds) based on maximum sustained wind speed, providing an estimate of potential property damage for each category.": "",
  "What is the Enhanced Fujita (EF) Scale?": "",
  "A scale that predicts where tornadoes will form": "",
  "A rating system (EF0 to EF5) that estimates tornado wind speeds based on the observed damage they produce": "",
  "A system for rating blizzard severity": "",
  "A scale that measures earthquake damage": "",
  "The Enhanced Fujita Scale rates tornadoes from EF0 (light damage, 105-137 km/h) to EF5 (incredible destruction, 322+ km/h) based on damage indicators, since tornado winds are rarely measured directly.": "",
  "What is a microburst?": "",
  "A sudden, powerful downdraft from a thunderstorm that produces damaging outward-spreading winds at the surface": "",
  "A small-scale hurricane that forms over lakes": "",
  "A very small tornado with winds under 100 km/h": "",
  "A brief burst of heavy rain that lasts less than one minute": "",
  "A microburst is a concentrated, powerful downdraft from a thunderstorm that strikes the ground and spreads outward, producing wind shear and gusts that can exceed 150 km/h, making them extremely dangerous for aircraft during takeoff and landing.": "",
  "What is wind shear?": "",
  "The constant speed of wind at a given altitude": "",
  "A change in wind speed or direction over a short distance, which is important for both tornado formation and hurricane intensity": "",
  "The friction between wind and the ground surface": "",
  "The maximum wind speed recorded during a storm": "",
  "Wind shear is a change in wind speed or direction over a short distance or height, and it plays dual roles in severe weather: it helps create the rotation needed for supercell thunderstorms and tornadoes, but it can disrupt and weaken hurricanes.": "",
  "What is the eyewall of a hurricane?": "",
  "The outer edge of the hurricane where it meets clear air": "",
  "The ring of intense thunderstorms surrounding the eye that contains the hurricane's strongest winds and heaviest rainfall": "",
  "The calm center of the hurricane where skies are clear": "",
  "The spiral rainbands that extend hundreds of kilometers from the center": "",
  "The eyewall is the ring of towering cumulonimbus clouds immediately surrounding the eye, and it is the most dangerous part of a hurricane, containing the strongest sustained winds, most intense rainfall, and greatest storm surge potential.": "",
  "What is storm surge?": "",
  "An abnormal rise in sea level generated by a storm's winds and low pressure, pushing a dome of water ashore": "",
  "A sudden increase in electrical current during a lightning storm": "",
  "Heavy rainfall flooding caused by a hurricane's thunderstorms": "",
  "The normal rise and fall of ocean tides during a storm": "",
  "Storm surge is an abnormal rise of water above the predicted astronomical tide, generated by hurricane-force winds pushing ocean water toward shore and the storm's low central pressure allowing water to rise, and it can raise sea levels by 6 meters or more.": "",
  "Hurricane Katrina (2005) caused catastrophic flooding in New Orleans primarily because:": "",
  "The hurricane's winds destroyed every building in the city": "",
  "Storm surge overwhelmed and breached the city's levee system, flooding areas that sit below sea level": "",
  "Heavy snowfall from the blizzard conditions collapsed buildings": "",
  "A tornado spawned by the hurricane devastated the entire city": "",
  "Hurricane Katrina's storm surge overwhelmed the levee and flood wall system protecting New Orleans, and because much of the city sits below sea level, the breached levees allowed floodwaters to inundate approximately 80% of the city, causing approximately 1,800 deaths.": "",
  "A family in Oklahoma hears a tornado warning for their county. The safest place for them to shelter is:": "",
  "In a basement or interior room on the lowest floor, away from windows, protected by heavy furniture or mattresses": "",
  "On the second floor of their house near a window to watch the tornado": "",
  "In their car, driving away from the tornado at high speed": "",
  "Under a highway overpass, which provides shelter from the wind": "",
  "The safest location during a tornado is a basement or, if no basement is available, an interior room (bathroom, closet) on the lowest floor away from windows, where the structure provides the most protection from flying debris, which causes most tornado injuries.": "",
  "Climate scientists predict that as ocean temperatures continue to rise, hurricanes may become more intense. This is because:": "",
  "Warmer water provides more energy through evaporation and latent heat release, which fuels stronger storms and heavier rainfall": "",
  "Warmer oceans produce stronger trade winds that spin hurricanes faster": "",
  "Rising sea levels make it easier for hurricanes to form over shallow water": "",
  "Warmer oceans reduce the Coriolis effect, allowing hurricanes to spin more freely": "",
  "Warmer ocean waters provide more energy to hurricanes through increased evaporation, and the warmer atmosphere can hold more moisture (about 7% more per degree Celsius), potentially producing hurricanes with stronger winds and significantly heavier rainfall.": "",
  "Hurricanes do not form within about 5 degrees of the equator because:": "",
  "The Coriolis effect is too weak near the equator to initiate the rotation needed for hurricane development": "",
  "Ocean temperatures are too cold near the equator": "",
  "Air pressure is too high at the equator for storms to form": "",
  "Constant trade winds at the equator tear hurricanes apart": "",
  "The Coriolis effect, which is caused by Earth's rotation and is essential for giving hurricanes their spin, approaches zero at the equator, so there is insufficient rotational force to organize a tropical disturbance into a rotating hurricane.": "",
  "During a severe blizzard, a motorist becomes stranded on a highway. The greatest immediate danger to the motorist is:": "",
  "Lightning strikes from the blizzard": "",
  "Hypothermia and frostbite from extreme cold combined with wind chill, especially if they leave their vehicle": "",
  "Flooding from the melting snow": "",
  "Tornadoes that commonly form within blizzards": "",
  "Blizzard conditions with high winds and cold temperatures create dangerous wind chill values that can cause frostbite in minutes, and hypothermia is the greatest risk for stranded individuals, which is why safety experts advise staying in the vehicle and running the engine periodically for heat.": "",
  "A meteorologist observes a hook echo on Doppler radar within a severe thunderstorm. This radar signature strongly indicates:": "",
  "The storm contains a rotating mesocyclone and a tornado may be forming or already present": "",
  "The storm is weakening and will dissipate soon": "",
  "Heavy rainfall is the only significant threat from the storm": "",
  "The storm is producing large hail but no tornado threat": "",
  "A hook echo on Doppler radar is a distinctive curved appendage in the radar reflectivity pattern that indicates precipitation being wrapped around a mesocyclone (rotating updraft), strongly suggesting tornado formation is occurring or imminent.": "",
  "A coastal community is evacuated before a hurricane because the forecast calls for 4-meter storm surge. If the hurricane arrives during high tide, the actual water level could be:": "",
  "Exactly 4 meters regardless of tidal conditions": "",
  "Significantly higher than 4 meters because storm surge adds on top of the astronomical high tide": "",
  "Zero because high tide prevents storm surge from forming": "",
  "Lower than the 4-meter forecast because high tide counteracts storm surge": "",
  "Storm surge combines with the astronomical tide to produce what is called storm tide, so a 4-meter storm surge arriving during a 1.5-meter high tide would result in water levels 5.5 meters above normal low tide, making the flooding significantly worse.": "",
  "The 2021 Texas freeze caused widespread power outages lasting days in freezing temperatures. The primary infrastructure failure was that:": "",
  "Natural gas pipelines, power plants, and wind turbines were not winterized for extreme cold, causing simultaneous failures across multiple energy sources": "",
  "Transmission lines from other states were deliberately disconnected": "",
  "All solar panels were covered in snow and could not generate electricity": "",
  "The power grid was overloaded by people using too many electric heaters": "",
  "The Texas freeze revealed that the state's energy infrastructure was not designed for extreme cold: natural gas wellheads and pipelines froze, some wind turbines lacked cold-weather packages, and power plant equipment failed, causing cascading outages across the grid.": "",
  "A pilot encounters a microburst during final approach to an airport. The most dangerous aspect of this situation is:": "",
  "Hail damage to the aircraft's engines": "",
  "Lightning strikes disabling the aircraft's instruments": "",
  "The sudden, powerful downdraft and resulting wind shear that can cause the aircraft to lose altitude rapidly when close to the ground": "",
  "Heavy rain reducing visibility through the windshield": "",
  "Microbursts produce intense wind shear that is extremely dangerous to aircraft, particularly during takeoff and landing when the aircraft is close to the ground: the pilot first encounters a headwind (lifting the aircraft), followed by a powerful downdraft and then a tailwind (causing rapid altitude loss).": "",
  "Emergency managers in a hurricane-prone coastal city are developing an evacuation plan. The most critical factor they should consider when determining evacuation zones is:": "",
  "The potential storm surge height for different hurricane categories combined with local elevation and topography": "",
  "The historical frequency of hurricanes hitting the area": "",
  "The number of hospitals in each zone": "",
  "Wind speed forecasts for different parts of the city": "",
  "Since storm surge is the deadliest hurricane hazard, evacuation zones are primarily based on storm surge inundation maps that model how far water would penetrate inland for different hurricane categories, combined with local elevation data to identify which areas would be flooded.": ""
}